nseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Protein requirements increase by 50% above non-pregnant levels","Iron requirements decrease in the third trimester","Folate requirements remain unchanged","Vitamin B12 requirements increase 50-fold","Calcium requirements double in all pregnant women"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring pregnancy, \u003Cstrong\u003Eprotein requirements increase by approximately 50%\u003C/strong\u003E above non-pregnant levels. This increased demand supports fetal growth, placental development, and maternal tissue expansion including breast and uterine growth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron requirements decrease in the third trimester\u003C/strong\u003E: Iron requirements actually increase throughout pregnancy to support expanded maternal blood volume and fetal demands\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFolate requirements remain unchanged\u003C/strong\u003E: Folate requirements double to 600 micrograms daily during pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin B12 requirements increase 50-fold\u003C/strong\u003E: While B12 requirements do increase slightly, the increase is modest, not 50-fold\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium requirements double in all pregnant women\u003C/strong\u003E: Calcium supplementation is only recommended for women at risk of pre-eclampsia or with low dietary intake\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding increased nutritional requirements during pregnancy is essential for preventing complications and supporting optimal fetal development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Protein requirements increase by 50% during pregnancy to support fetal growth and maternal tissue expansion.","